{"slug":"core-periphery","graph":"companies","title":"Core and crust","sub":"who holds the middle of the market — and is the core even real?","headline":"<strong>10 of 56</strong> companies sit in the prospect quadrant — central in the money network but peripheral in the business network (Commure, Patronus AI, Hebbia, …). One caution: the market's “core” looks no more special than its edge counts alone would predict (p = 0.90), so read “core” as “well-connected,” nothing more.","prose":{"intro":"<p>Every market has an establishment and a crust. We ask three things. Which companies hold the middle of the agent ecosystem? Is that core a real structure, or just who happens to have the most edges? And the actionable one: who is central in the money network but peripheral in the business network — well-financed, but not yet embedded in deals? Those companies need partners.</p>","how":"<p>Each company gets a score from 0 (crust) to 1 (core), fitted so that high scorers hold most of the map's edges in the classic establishment shape: core companies connect to everyone including each other, crust companies connect only to the core. We compute it three times — on all 523 ties, on business ties only, and on shared-investor ties only. Then a reality check: rewire the map at random 500 times, keeping each company's number of ties, and re-fit. The real map does not beat the rewired ones (p = 0.90), and the score tracks raw tie count almost exactly (correlation 0.85) — so the overall core is largely popularity in disguise. The useful signal is in the split: crossing the money score against the business score separates the establishment (high on both) from the prospects (financed, not yet embedded).</p>","method":"<p>Rombach et al., “Core-Periphery Structure in Networks (Revisited)”, SIAM Review 59(3), 2017 — continuous coreness via the cpnet implementation (label switching, α=0.5, β=0.8, best of 10 runs; the kernel maps ranks onto two blocks, crust ≤ 0.25 and core ≥ 0.75, so the quadrant guides at the axis midpoints split exactly core-block vs crust-block). Significance: Kojaku &amp; Masuda's (q,s)-test (Scientific Reports 8:7351, 2018) with 500 Chung-Lu expected-degree null graphs; Rombach yields a single core-periphery pair, so significance is all-or-nothing across the 186 nodes — here: not significant. Determinism note: cpnet's inner loop is numba-jitted and uses numba's own RNG, which numpy seeding does not touch; we seed numpy, python, and numba (via a jitted np.random.seed) and verify by double-run. The method needs no connected graph: all 186 non-isolated companies across 5 components are scored, and small components land in the crust by construction.</p>"},"caveat":"9 of our 14 rivals land in the core mostly because the 27 security vendors all point competitor edges at each other. AoC itself is crust: rank 117 of 188 on 5 thin edges (4 rival ties + 1 unverified business tie), and with no shared-investor edges at all it cannot appear on the quadrant chart. Two of the 10 “prospects” are competitor-flagged.","inputs":{"companies":{"nodes":188,"edges":530}},"data":{"quadrant":[{"id":"ai21-labs","label":"AI21 Labs","x":0.1,"y":0.1646,"group":"frontier-lab"},{"id":"ambience-healthcare","label":"Ambience Healthcare","x":0.1417,"y":0.2373,"group":"healthcare"},{"id":"anthropic","label":"Anthropic","x":0.9891,"y":0.975,"group":"frontier-lab"},{"id":"baseten","label":"Baseten","x":0.0639,"y":0.8625,"group":"infra-platform"},{"id":"bolt-stackblitz","label":"Bolt (StackBlitz)","x":0.8478,"y":0.1266,"group":"agent-native-startup"},{"id":"brex","label":"Brex","x":0.1889,"y":0.7875,"group":"bank-fintech"},{"id":"browserbase","label":"Browserbase","x":0.0722,"y":0.2184,"group":"infra-platform"},{"id":"calypsoai","label":"CalypsoAI","x":0.0917,"y":0.8,"group":"security-eval-vendor"},{"id":"cerebras","label":"Cerebras","x":0.1056,"y":0.2057,"group":"infra-platform"},{"id":"clay","label":"Clay","x":0.2056,"y":0.1171,"group":"agent-native-startup"},{"i